    "Question": {
      "content": "The following are conductors except",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "silver",
        "copper",
        "aluminium",
        "plastic"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "plastic"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<div style='font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;'><h3 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Conductors vs. Insulators</h3><p>Conductors allow electric current due to free electrons, while insulators resist current flow.</p><h4 style='color: #2c3e50; margin-top: 15px;'>Analysis of Options:</h4><table style='width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;'><tr><th style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; background: #f2f2f2;'>Material</th><th style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; background: #f2f2f2;'>Property</th></tr><tr><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Silver</td><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Best conductor (highest conductivity)</td></tr><tr><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Copper</td><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Common conductor (wiring, electronics)</td></tr><tr><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Aluminium</td><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Conductor (used in power lines)</td></tr><tr><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; background: #ffebee;'><strong>Plastic</strong></td><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; background: #ffebee;'><strong>Insulator (no free electrons)</strong></td></tr></table><p>Thus, <strong>plastic</strong> is the exception among the given options.</p></div>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electric Current",
      "Resistance",
      "Conductors and Insulators"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 7 @ 2022/2023",
    "Question": {
      "content": "A piece of copper has a resistance of 12.0Ω. If it is compressed so that the length is halved and the area is tripled. What is the new resistance?",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "6 Ω",
        "5 Ω",
        "4 Ω",
        "2 Ω"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "2 Ω"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<div style='font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;'><h3 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Resistance and Geometry</h3><p>Resistance (<em>R</em>) depends on resistivity (<em>ρ</em>), length (<em>L</em>), and cross-sectional area (<em>A</em>):</p><p style='background: #f8f9fa; padding: 10px; border-left: 4px solid #3498db;'><strong>R = ρ(L/A)</strong></p><h4 style='color: #2c3e50; margin-top: 15px;'>Given Changes:</h4><ul><li>Original: <em>R</em> = 12 Ω, <em>L</em>, <em>A</em></li><li>New: <em>L'</em> = <em>L</em>/2, <em>A'</em> = 3<em>A</em></li></ul><h4 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Calculation:</h4><p><strong>New resistance:</strong> <em>R'</em> = ρ(<em>L'</em>/<em>A'</em>) = ρ[(<em>L</em>/2)/(3<em>A</em>)] = (1/6) × ρ(<em>L</em>/<em>A</em>) = (1/6) × 12 Ω = <strong>2 Ω</strong>.</p><p>Thus, the new resistance is <strong>2 Ω</strong>.</p></div>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Resistance",
      "Electric Current",
      "Conductors and Insulators",
      "Resistivity"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 9 @ 2022/2023",
    "Question": {
      "content": "Tungsten has a resistivity of 5.6x10⁻⁸Ωm. What is the resistance of a 1.2m long tungsten wire with a radius of 1.0x10⁻³m",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "0.300Ω",
        "0.0210Ω",
        "0.050Ω",
        "0.0010Ω"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "0.0210Ω"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<div style='font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;'><h3 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Resistance Calculation</h3><p>Resistance (<em>R</em>) is calculated using:</p><p style='background: #f8f9fa; padding: 10px; border-left: 4px solid #3498db;'><strong>R = ρ(L/A)</strong></p><p>Where:</p><ul><li><strong>ρ</strong> (resistivity) = 5.6 × 10<sup>−8</sup> Ωm</li><li><strong>L</strong> (length) = 1.2 m</li><li><strong>A</strong> (area) = πr² = π × (1.0 × 10<sup>−3</sup> m)² ≈ 3.1416 × 10<sup>−6</sup> m²</li></ul><h4 style='color: #2c3e50; margin-top: 15px;'>Step-by-Step:</h4><p><strong>1. Calculate A:</strong><br>A = π × (1.0 × 10<sup>−3</sup>)² = 3.1416 × 10<sup>−6</sup> m²</p><p><strong>2. Plug into formula:</strong><br>R = (5.6 × 10<sup>−8</sup>) × (1.2)/(3.1416 × 10<sup>−6</sup>)</p><p><strong>3. Simplify:</strong><br>≈ 5.6 × 1.2 / 3.1416 × 10<sup>−2</sup> ≈ 0.0214 Ω</p><p>Rounding to four significant figures: <strong>0.0210 Ω</strong>.</p></div>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electricity & Magnetism",
      "Resistance",
      "Resistivity",
      "Conductors and Insulators",
      "Electric Current"
    ]
