  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 10 @ 2022/2023",
    "Question": {
      "content": "A material that provides zero resistance to electrical currents at a certain temperature called the critical temperature is called",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "dielectric",
        "capacitor",
        "superconductor",
        "insulator"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "superconductor"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<div style='font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;'><h3 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Understanding Superconductors</h3><p>A material exhibiting <strong>zero electrical resistance</strong> below a specific <em>critical temperature (T<sub>c</sub>)</em> is termed a <strong>superconductor</strong>. This phenomenon, called <strong>superconductivity</strong>, was first discovered in mercury at 4.2 K.</p><h4 style='color: #2c3e50; margin-top: 15px;'>Key Properties:</h4><ul><li><strong>Zero resistance:</strong> Infinite conductivity with no energy loss.</li><li><strong>Critical temperature (T<sub>c</sub>):</strong> Material-specific threshold (e.g., Nb<sub>3</sub>Sn at 18 K).</li><li><strong>Meissner effect:</strong> Expulsion of magnetic fields.</li></ul><h4 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Why Other Options Are Incorrect:</h4><table style='width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 15px 0;'><tr><th style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; background: #f2f2f2;'>Option</th><th style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px; background: #f2f2f2;'>Explanation</th></tr><tr><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Dielectric</td><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Insulator used in capacitors (e.g., ceramic).</td></tr><tr><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Capacitor</td><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Energy-storage device, not a material.</td></tr><tr><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>Insulator</td><td style='border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 8px;'>High-resistance material (e.g., rubber).</td></tr></table><p>Thus, <strong>superconductor</strong> is the only correct answer.</p></div>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electricity & Magnetism",
      "Resistance",
      "Electric Current",
      "Conductors and Insulators",
      "Superconductivity"
    ]
  },
